properties.Other Information:
The original salmon population in the Thames became extinct in the 1830s. The Rehabilitation Scheme began in 1979, using fish donated by the fish farming industry and adults returning from these as broodstock. This changed in the mid 1990s and the salmon stocked into the Thames were a mixture of fish from line-bred hatcheries on the  Shannon and Delphi in Ireland.  These were either stocked as fry or smolts. All salmon stocking into the Thames catchment ceased in 2011.
Significant Recovery and / or Management Actions: Fishpasses were constructed on the Thames weirs to assist salmon migration.  These were mostly Denil, although a few were Larinier.  The weirs at Molesey and Sunbury also had traps so salmon could be tagged and tracked up the river.  The River Kennet also benefited from fishpasses.  These were also a mixture of Denil and Larinier fishpasses.  The TWUL water intakes have had screening added to stop the impingement of fish including migrating salmon smolts. The Thames Tideway Tunnel should improve water quality through the tidal river in summer.
Special Designations: Recovering Salmon River. The River Kennet is designated SSSI. Salmon were introduced into the River Lambourn, which is a tributary of the Kennet and is designated a SAC.
Specific Threats: Weirs associated with navigation on the Thames causing fish passage issues.  Water quantity is an issue in the summer months because of very large abstractions for potable supply. Water quality affects fish populations, both from discharges and river temperature in summer months. Poor water quality through tideway during/after heavy rain due to CSO's.  Because the Thames is a navigation the distance to suitable spawning habitat is confined to tributaries of the Thames.  The most suitable was deemed to be the River Kennet and this is over 50 miles from the tideway.  The Thames has a number of large abstractions which can impact on flows in the Thames and therefore salmon migration both as juveniles leaving the river and adults returning and moving up river.

Very little known about the state of the salmon stock. Infrequent electrofishing monitoring at one loaction in the lower catchment. Extremely low angling effort, almost exclusively focused on brown trout.
Special Designations: Recovering Salmon River
Specific Threats: Steep moorland catchment that discharges to sea via a small shingle beach. The river mouth is frequently inaccessible to migratory fish due to natural build-up of shingle. River often flows though the shingle which also impacts ability for smolts to reach the sea.

Late run salmon stock. 
Significant Recovery and / or Management Actions: Land management strategies. Some agriculture and habitat restoration work in East Looe following a massive fish kill downstream of a STW. Over 200 dead sea trout and a salmon collected but losses probably double that at least. 
Special Designations: Recovering Salmon River. The Looe Rivers flow directly into the Whitsand and Looe Bay MCZ.
Specific Threats:  East and West Looe: Barriers to migration. Fairly steep catchments with agricuture & siltation issues. Carnon landfill discharges to W Looe. Historic mining influences. East Looe: Active railway line right alongside the river affects river geomorphology. Large industrial estate at Moorswater and sewage treatment works discharges.  Potential for a future large estuary width flood barrier scheme in the harbour that could prevent upstream migration route at times of spring tides and storm seas. Illegal gill netting in the East & West Looe estuaries and in the coastal areas around Cawsands, Looe island and towards Polperro/Fowey.

Very limited knowledge about this stock. Lower Otter supports better habitat for spawning gravels. Populations of beavers present throughout catchment and extending into tributaries.
Significant Recovery and / or Management Actions: Two Landscape Recovery Schemes planned in lower and upper catchment (currently in planning phase) with links to improving fisheries habitat and removing barriers. Project in early stages to address some barriers. Land management strategies. 
Special Designations: Recovering Salmon River. Otter Estuary SSSI
Specific Threats: Unstable river gravels, diffuse pollution from agriculture and barriers to migration.

Salmon only present in the River Tone catchment of the R. Parrett
Significant Recovery and / or Management Actions: Some work on fish passage improvement, some habitat improvement work
Special Designations: Recovering Salmon River
Specific Threats:  Barriers, water quality, invasive species, sediment

Minewater affected & fishless headwaters. Fish diversity increases downstream to include bullhead, sea trout and eels. 
Significant Recovery and / or Management Actions: Broad plans to improve instream habitat in lower river to prevent erosion of toe of main road to Seaton beach. Potential for much improved spawning habitat.
Special Designations: Recovering Salmon River. The Seaton River flows directly into the Whitsand and Looe Bay MCZ.
Specific Threats: Minewater discharge in headwaters. Agricultural run off.

Late run salmon stock. 
Significant Recovery and / or Management Actions: Major intervention at Boscastle after extreme flood event. New deeper river channel artificially carved out of the existing constrained channel bedrock through Boscastle. New deeper river channel created over about 0.5mile.
Special Designations: Recovering Salmon River. The Valency estuary is part of the Hartland Point to Tintagel MCZ and seaward it joins the Bristol Channel Approaches SAC.
Specific Threats: Fish farm on the catchment (brown trout and rainbow trout). Very steep valley sides, rapid impact from agricultural runoff. A previous extreme flood event affected this whole catchment.

Change operational schedule of sluice between fjord and open sea in order to reduce mortality of both smolt and adult salmon. Removal of remaining migrational obstacles. Reduce avian predation (cormorants) during parr and smolt stage. Continued need for restriction of recreational catches (harvest) of spawners. Continued need for restriction of recreational catches (harvest) of spawners.
